    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv from the current directory. For each file, return a compact summary with the following fields: file_name, row_count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, up to 20 unique cmdb_id values, up to 20 unique KPI/trace/log names (use kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv), and the top 5 rows sample (for metric/trace/log include columns timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name/trace_name/log_name, value; for error_logs include timestamp, cmdb_id, message). Keep output concise and return only these aggregates (no full raw dumps)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full metric series and counted anomalies in the incident window (07:30–08:00 CST). Most flagged series are static/start-time/capacity metrics (e.g., runtime.java_lang_Runtime_StartTime, container_start_time_seconds, system.disk.total) that are at or above their P95 at every timestamp and are not actionable. To find real failures we must focus on dynamic performance KPIs (CPU, memory, network, latency, error rates, request counts, read/write I/O) and exclude static/capacity/start-time metrics. Next, we should narrow the candidate series by excluding KPI name patterns related to start time, total capacity, and other stable metrics, and then surface the top dynamic-series with anomalies (anomaly_count>0) for further inspection (earliest anomaly times, severity). This will let us identify which components and KPIs show meaningful consecutive breaches during the incident window.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the previously computed per-series aggregates (global_P95 and window aggregates saved in kernel variables), filter the series to exclude KPI names matching these patterns (case-insensitive substring match): 'start_time', 'container_start_time', 'runtime.java_lang', 'system.disk.total', 'disk.total', 'uptime', 'capacity', 'node_boot_time'. From the remaining series, keep only those with anomaly_count > 0. Return a compact table (max 20 rows) ordered by anomaly_count desc then by max_value_in_window desc with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window. Also return: (1) the total number of series after filtering, and (2) the top 10 distinct kpi_name substrings (kpi_name tokens) present in these series to help pick dynamic KPI families (e.g., cpu, memory, app.http.count, app.grpc.*, system.load, network.*). Keep output concise and do not print full raw timeseries."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have computed global P95 thresholds and identified many series flagged as anomalous in the incident window, but most are static/start-time or capacity metrics and some memory metrics that stay at their P95 for the whole window. We filtered out obvious static metrics and kept dynamic KPI families; there remain ~4,601 series with anomaly_count>0, and top tokens include istio/mesh/grpc/request/response which are promising for real failures. Next we need to prioritize KPI families (tokenized kpi_name groups) to find which dynamic metric families show concentrated anomalies (high number of affected series, earliest anomaly times, and high total anomalies). This will guide targeted metric inspection, trace correlation, and log analysis to localize the two failures.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the per-series aggregates already stored in kernel variables (the filtered set that excludes static/start-time/disk/capacity metrics and contains only series with anomaly_count>0), do the following:\n1) For each kpi_name generate a token = the first two dot-separated segments of kpi_name (if only one segment exists, use that segment). Example: 'app.grpc.count' -> 'app.grpc', 'container.node-6.container_memory_rss' -> 'container.node-6'.\n2) Group series by this token and compute these aggregates per token: series_count (number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) series), series_with_anomaly_count (number of series in the group with anomaly_count>0 — should equal series_count here), total_anomaly_points (sum of anomaly_count across series in the group), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (minimum earliest_anomaly_timestamp across series), and up to 5 representative kpi_name examples from the group.\n3) Return a compact table limited to top 20 tokens ordered by total_anomaly_points descending, with columns: token, series_count, total_anomaly_points, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, representative_kpi_names (list up to 5). Also return the total number of tokens found.\nKeep output concise and do not print full raw series. Save the grouped token aggregates in a kernel variable for the next steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We grouped filtered anomalous metric series into tokens and found the highest anomaly volumes come from: container.node-6 (many container.memory_* series), mesh.source and mesh.destination (Istio/mesh traffic metrics), container.node-5, plus system.swap, system.net, app.grpc, and system.io. Earliest anomalies for top tokens are at 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST. These point to two high-priority investigation paths: (1) node/container resource issues on node-6 (and node-5) — many containers show memory at/above P95 for the whole window; (2) service-to-service mesh/istio traffic anomalies (source/destination) which may indicate networking or request-level problems. To localize the two failures we must now analyze traces to see which services/traces show latency or error-rate anomalies in the incident window and whether those trace anomalies correlate with the metric candidates (node-6 containers and mesh paths). Trace analysis will help identify the downstream faulty service/container appearing in traces and give precise timestamps for failure starts.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Perform trace-level anomaly detection on trace.csv as follows and store results in kernel variables for later steps: 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 using the full trace.csv series. 2) Filter trace.csv to the incident window 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST through 2022-03-21 08:00:00 CST. 3) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) in the filtered window compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (number of rows with value >= global_P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first timestamp where value >= P95), and max_value_in_window. 4) Return a compact table (max 20 rows) ordered by anomaly_count desc then by max_value_in_window desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_P95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window. 5) Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) series processed and how many had anomaly_count > 0. Keep output concise and do not print full raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace-level analysis was completed: global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) was computed and the incident-window (07:30–07:59 CST) points were compared to those thresholds. Results show every trace series was flagged because many trace metrics have global_P95 == 0.0 and constant zero values in the window, so these are not actionable. Therefore, traces with non-zero baselines or non-zero spikes must be isolated. From metric token analysis, the highest-impact metric families are container.memory on node-6 (and node-5) and mesh.source/mesh.destination (Istio). This suggests two parallel investigation paths: (A) node/container resource issues centered on node-6 (many containers show memory at/above P95 across the whole window), and (B) service-to-service mesh networking anomalies. To localize the two failures we should first identify which pods run on node-6 (using container.node-6.* KPI series) and inspect whether those pods show sustained anomalies (anomaly_count == total_points_in_window) and earliest anomaly times. This will tell us candidate pod-level root causes and their exact first anomalous timestamps to match to the two failures. After that, we will inspect traces with non-zero baselines and mesh metrics correlated to those pods. No final root-cause determination yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the previously saved per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) window-aggregates (the filtered set excluding static metrics), select series where kpi_name contains the substring 'container.node-6' (case-insensitive). Group by cmdb_id and compute for each cmdb_id: series_count (number of distinct kpi_name series on node-6 for that cmdb_id), total_anomaly_points (sum of anomaly_count across those series), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (minimum earliest_anomaly_timestamp across those series), always_anomalous_series_count (count of series where anomaly_count == total_points_in_window), and up to 5 representative kpi_name examples. Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows ordered by series_count desc then total_anomaly_points desc, with columns: cmdb_id, series_count, total_anomaly_points, always_anomalous_series_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, representative_kpi_names. Also return the total number of distinct cmdb_id values found on node-6. Keep output concise and do not print raw full time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric token and node-6 analyses and trace-level P95 comparisons. Key derivations so far: (1) a large, persistent set of container memory metrics on node-6 (many pods show values at/above their P95 across the entire 07:30–08:00 window) with earliest anomalies at 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST — this strongly suggests a node-6 related resource issue affecting many pods starting at 07:30. (2) mesh.source and mesh.destination token groups show high anomaly volumes (earliest 07:30), indicating service-to-service/istio traffic anomalies around the same time. (3) Trace.csv results were mostly non-actionable because many trace metrics have global_P95 == 0.0 and constant zeros. To localize the two failures we must now (A) find actionable trace anomalies by focusing on trace series with non-zero global_P95 (these indicate real latency/error baselines and potential spikes), and (B) inspect logs for error_count or row_count drops for services that run on node-6 and/or appear in problematic mesh paths. Finding trace series with non-zero baselines will give precise downstream faulty services and exact first-anomaly timestamps; log analysis will help determine the underlying reason (e.g., OOMs, connection failures). No final root-cause assignments yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the trace per-series aggregates already computed and saved in kernel variables: 1) Filter to series where global_P95 > 0 AND anomaly_count > 0. 2) Return a compact table (max 20 rows) ordered by anomaly_count desc then max_value_in_window desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_P95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window. 3) Also return the total count of trace series that meet global_P95 > 0 and anomaly_count > 0. Keep output concise and do not print full raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We filtered traces to actionable ones (global_P95 > 0) and found many inter-service row_count traces (frontend → checkout → payment/email) with earliest anomalies at 07:30–07:31 CST, but many values merely equal historical P95 (row_count == 1.0). Metric analysis strongly points to a node-6 issue: many containers across many services on node-6 show container.memory_* series anomalous for the entire 07:30–08:00 window with earliest anomalous timestamp 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST. Mesh.source/mesh.destination token groups also show large anomaly volumes starting at 07:30. To distinguish two separate failures we need corroborating evidence from logs: if some services show error_count or sudden drops in row_count or other log-based indicators around specific times, that will help assign failure events to either a node-level resource problem (node-6) or a network/mesh problem (istio) and provide exact occurrence times. Next step is to scan log.csv for any non-zero error_count or abrupt log signals in the incident window for the candidate services (especially those mapped to node-6 and services in frontend→checkout→payment paths).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log.csv, do the following and save results in kernel variables: 1) Filter log.csv to the incident window 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST through 2022-03-21 08:00:00 CST. 2) For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute: total_points_in_window, sum_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, earliest_nonzero_timestamp (the earliest timestamp where value > 0; null if none). 3) Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows where sum_value_in_window > 0, ordered by sum_value_in_window desc, with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, total_points_in_window, sum_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, earliest_nonzero_timestamp. 4) Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id, log_name) series processed and the number with sum_value_in_window > 0. Keep output concise and do not print full raw timeseries."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through preprocessing, metric anomaly detection, trace filtering, and log inspection. Key findings so far: (1) A widespread, persistent container memory anomaly affecting many pods placed on node-6, with earliest anomalies at 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST — this is a strong candidate for one failure (node-6 resource/memory issue). (2) Large anomaly volumes in mesh.source and mesh.destination (Istio) metrics beginning at 07:30, and node-level disk I/O spikes on node-4/node-5 and TCP retransmission increases on node-2 — these point to a second, likely network/IO-related failure beginning around the same time. Traces mostly had zero baselines, but actionable traces concentrate on frontend→checkout→payment/email paths with earliest anomalies at 07:30–07:31 CST. Logs show heavy frontend throughput at 07:30 but no dominant error spikes. We still need to confirm the second failure's exact root cause component and timestamp (network vs node IO) by targeting mesh metrics (identify affected services and earliest anomalous timestamps) and by correlating those to node-level network or IO anomalies. No final root-cause assignments yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the stored metric per-series aggregates (global_P95 and window aggregates), focus on Istio/mesh metrics: 1) Select series where kpi_name contains 'mesh.source' OR 'mesh.destination' (case-insensitive). 2) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute/return: global_P95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window. 3) Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows ordered by anomaly_count desc then max_value_in_window desc, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window. 4) Also return: (A) total number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) mesh series processed, and (B) number of those with anomaly_count > 0. Keep output concise and do not print raw full time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the required workflow: computed global thresholds, filtered the incident window (2022-03-21 07:30:00–08:00:00 CST), performed metric anomaly detection, traced actionable trace series, and inspected logs. Key findings: \n- Strong, persistent container memory anomalies across many pods scheduled on node-6 (36 distinct cmdb_id pods). Most container.memory_rss/cache series on node-6 are anomalous for the entire window with earliest anomaly 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST. This indicates a node-6 related resource issue affecting many pods starting at 07:30:00 CST.\n- Large, sustained mesh (Istio) anomalies (mesh.source and mesh.destination) beginning at 07:30:00 CST, with particularly large request/response volumes directed at adservice/adservice2 (absolute values well above their historical P95). Frontend logs show high row_count starting at 07:30:00 CST, but frontend app.http/app.grpc metrics do not show a matching abrupt spike at 07:30. Node-level I/O spikes (node-4/node-5) and TCP retransmissions (node-2) also appear near 07:30, indicating simultaneous resource/network activity.\n- Actionable trace series concentrate on frontend → checkout → payment/email paths with earliest anomalies 07:30–07:31 CST, and frontend logs show heavy ingress at 07:30:00 CST.\nDerivation so far: there are two plausible failures starting at or around 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST: (1) a node-6 container memory/resource incident affecting many pods (earliest anomaly 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST); (2) a mesh-level traffic/communication disturbance with heavy mesh.destination request/response volumes targeting adservice/adservice2 starting at 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST (correlated with elevated frontend ingress and node I/O/network anomalies). We need one more targeted metric check to precisely timestamp and confirm the mesh/adservice disturbance: retrieve mesh.destination series that target adservice or adservice2 and show their earliest anomaly times and magnitudes so we can solidify the second failure's root cause component and exact occurrence datetime.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the stored metric per-series aggregates (global_P95 and window aggregates), select series where kpi_name contains 'mesh.destination' AND contains 'adservice' (case-insensitive). For each matching (cmdb_id, kpi_name) return: global_P95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, and max_value_in_window. Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows ordered by max_value_in_window desc, and also return the total number of matching series and how many of them had anomaly_count > 0. Keep output concise and do not print raw full time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have traced two strong, separate anomaly clusters starting at the window start (2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST): (A) a concentrated set of container memory anomalies across many pods scheduled on node-6 (36 distinct pods showing container_memory_rss/cache at or above their historical P95 for every minute in the 07:30–08:00 window); (B) sustained elevated mesh (Istio) request/response volumes (mesh.source/mesh.destination) beginning at 07:30:00 CST, especially targeting adservice/adservice2, correlated with very high frontend log.row_count values at 07:30:00 CST and node-level IO/network anomalies on other nodes (node-4/node-5 I/O spikes, node-2 TCP retransmits).\n\nWhat we can derive so far: the first failure candidate is a node-6–related resource problem (many containers on node-6 ubiquitously anomalous starting at 07:30:00 CST). The second failure candidate is a mesh/traffic disturbance (sustained elevated mesh.destination toward adservice/adservice2 starting 07:30:00 CST) possibly driven by high system-wide throughput (frontends) or by mesh/network degradation; traces & logs show heavy traffic on frontend→checkout→payment paths but frontend app metrics do not indicate a single abrupt frontend spike at 07:30—rather, overall high throughput is present. We still need to confirm whether the node-6 issue is best described as node-level memory consumption (node-6) or as many containers having high memory independent of node host metrics; and for the mesh issue we need to confirm the precise affected service(s) and exact earliest anomalous timestamp(s) at the service/pod level (to pick a root-cause component among the allowed list).\n\nTherefore the next atomic step is to inspect the available node-6 host KPIs so we can confirm whether host-level memory/swap or other node KPIs show anomalies that justify selecting node-6 as the root-cause component and the root cause reason (e.g., \"node memory consumption\").",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, select all rows where cmdb_id == 'node-6'. For each unique kpi_name for node-6 compute (using the full series) the global_P95, then restrict to the incident window 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST through 2022-03-21 08:00:00 CST and compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (value >= global_P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first timestamp where value >= P95), and max_value_in_window. Return a compact table limited to the top 50 kpi_name rows ordered by anomaly_count desc then max_value_in_window desc, with columns: kpi_name, global_P95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window. Also return the total number of distinct kpi_name values for node-6 and the number of those with anomaly_count > 0. Keep output concise and do not print raw full timeseries."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed preprocess -> anomaly detection -> fault identification -> root cause localization steps across metric, trace, and log data. What has been done: computed global P95 thresholds, filtered the incident window (2022-03-21 07:30:00–08:00:00 CST), and identified two dominant anomaly clusters starting at 07:30:00 CST: (1) widespread container memory metrics on node-6 (many pods showing container_memory_rss/cache at-or-above P95 for every minute of the window), strongly indicating a node-6 resource issue affecting many pods starting at 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST; (2) sustained elevated Istio/mesh destination/request/response volumes (mesh.source/mesh.destination) beginning at 07:30:00 CST, especially toward adservice/adservice2, correlated with high frontend log.row_count and node IO/network anomalies on other nodes (node-4/node-5 IO spikes, node-2 TCP retransmits). What can be derived: two concurrent failures are plausible — a node-level memory/resource problem on node-6, and a mesh/traffic disturbance impacting adservice(s). What remains missing to finalize root cause for each failure: confirmation of any container process terminations or OOM kills (which would support a container-level failure vs. node-level memory saturation), and confirmation whether mesh anomalies were driven by frontend-originated traffic surge (unlikely from frontend app.http metrics) or by mesh/network degradation (evidence in system.tcp retrans and mesh TCP metrics). Therefore we cannot finalize the two root-cause components and exact root timestamps yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Search metric.csv for any KPI names that indicate container restarts, OOMs, or process termination. Specifically, scan kpi_name (case-insensitive) for substrings: 'oom', 'oom_kill', 'oom_killer', 'restart', 'restarts', 'container_restart', 'process.exit', 'process.terminated', 'container.state', 'container.uptime'. For each matching (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global_P95 using the full series, then filter to the incident window 2022-03-21 07:30:00 CST through 2022-03-21 08:00:00 CST and compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (value >= global_P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (first timestamp where value >= P95), and max_value_in_window. Return a compact table limited to top 20 rows ordered by anomaly_count desc then max_value_in_window desc, and also return the total number of matching series. Keep output concise and do not print raw full time series."
}

